February manufacturing PMI of 52.6 (consensus 50.6) is stronger than Januaryâ€™s 50.1 and marks the fastest pace since Apr-122. China's factory activity stuns with fastest growth in a decade1. BEIJING  March 1 (Reuters) - China's manufacturing activity expanded at the fastest pace in more than a decade in February  an official index showed on Wednesday  smashing expectations as production zoomed after the lifting of COVID-19 restrictions late last year.2. The manufacturing purchasing managers' index (PMI) shot up to 52.6 from 50.1 in January  according to China's National Bureau of Statistics  above the 50-point mark that separates expansion and contraction in activity. The PMI far exceeded an analyst forecast of 50.5 and was the highest reading since April 2012.3. Global markets cheered the big surprise in the PMI with Asian stocks and the Australian dollar reversing earlier losses  the offshore yuan perking up and oil rallying  as investors took a more optimistic view on China's economic prospects.More here
